===Etymology===
From the Old Norse ''völu-'', ''vọlv-'', genitive of ''vọlva'' (''truth-sayer'', ''staff-carrier'', ''prophetess'').  (Cognate with the Gothic ''walus'', Old English ''wala'', ''walu'', Old Friesian ''walu''.)  ''Vọlva'' is from ''[[vọlr]]'' (''rounded staff''), from Proto-Norse ''*waluR'', from Germanic ''*waluz-''; possibly from PIE ''*uel-'' (''to turn'').

===Proper noun===
'''Völuspá'''
# The Prophecy of the [[vọlva|Vọlva]]; the first book of the [[Poetic Edda]].

